<DOC><DOCNO> AP890429-0109 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 1855EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-29 0377</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0389</SECOND><HEAD>Snow and Thunderstorms in the Mississippi Valley</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Spring snow fell Saturday across northeast Minnesota andnorthwest Wisconsin, thunderstorms caused hail in Texas and floodsoccurred in West Virginia and Ohio.   In Duluth, Minn., 5 inches of snow fell Saturday morning, andalmost half of it melted by noon.   Southwest Wyoming had snow showers.   The Texas thunderstorms produced hail as big as three-fourths ofan inch, as well as a quarter-inch of rain in one hour, inGalveston.   Similar size hail fell in Indianapolis.   Parts of West Virginia had flooding due to heavy rains. AroundMiddlebourne, in the part of the state bordering Ohio, severalroads were closed and many were covered with debris.   A flood warning continued over the Scioto River, which wasexpected to crest at Piketon, Ohio, around noon Sunday at 3{ feetabove flood stage.   A flood warning also was posted for the Miami River which was tocrest at about 1 foot above flood stage at Miamitown, Ohio,Saturday night.   Showers and thunderstorms reached from southern New York stateand Ohio to the Carolinas, southern Florida, the Florida Panhandle,central Alabama and the upper Texas Gulf Coast.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 33degrees at Duluth to 92 degrees at Sanford, Fla. The nation's lowSaturday morning was 7 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.   The forecast for Sunday called for rain showers scattered acrosscentral Nebraska and much of Minnesota and Wisconsin, and from NewEngland to eastern New York state, New Jersey and Pennsylvania.Rain and thunderstorms were predicted from Maryland to southernFlorida, and from the Tennessee Valley to the central Gulf Coaststates, Louisiana and the northeast third of Texas.   High temperatures were forecast in the upper 30s and 40s fromupper Michigan westward to the northern Plains, much of Nebraskaand northern Colorado; the 50s and 60s from New England to NewJersey and the rest of the Great Lakes states, from Missouri tocentral Arkansas, southeast Nebraska, Kansas, Oklahoma, the TexasPanhandle, the rest of Colorado, and from Montana to northern NewMexico, central Arizona, and much of California; in the upper 80sand 90s in the desert Southwest; and in the 70s and 80s elsewhere.</TEXT></DOC>